rom both the social sciences and the humanities conceive of East Asia's Confucian revival as a "habit of the heart," an underlying belief system that guides a society, and examine how Confucianism might function as a civil religion in China, Korea, and Japan. They discuss what aspects of Confucian tradition and thought are being embraced; some of the social movements, political factors, and opportunities connected with the revival of the tradition; and why Confucianism has not traveled much beyond East Asia. The late Robert Bellah's reflection on the possibility for a global civil religion concludes the volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil religion. 0aConfucianism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aSociology : Sociology of Religion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aBellah, Robert N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillioud, Sébastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Do-Hyun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvanhoe, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvanhoe, Philip J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKim, Sungmoon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Sungmoon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMadsen, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakajima, Takahiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeng, Guoxiang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSun, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r